/*
 * aws.config — AWS-specific configuration
 *
 * This is the cloud architecture from my design document.
 * The whole idea is: upload a VCF to S3, everything runs automatically,
 * results appear in the output bucket and the database.
 *
 * Cost controls:
 *   - Spot instances for imputation (biggest cost driver)
 *   - AWS Budget alerts at $100/month
 *   - CloudWatch dashboards for monitoring memory/CPU
 *   - Auto-shutdown when pipeline finishes (no idle instances)
 */

// ---- AWS Batch Compute Environments ----
// In production I'd have two compute environments:
//
// 1. prs-on-demand: for critical steps that can't be interrupted
//    (database writes, final scoring)
//
// 2. prs-spot: for compute-heavy steps where interruption is OK
//    (imputation — Nextflow retries automatically if a spot instance
//     gets reclaimed)
//
// Spot instances save 60-90% vs on-demand for the imputation step,
// which is where most of the compute cost goes.

// ---- S3 Bucket Structure ----
// s3://prs-pipeline-data/
//   ├── input/              # uploaded VCFs land here
//   │   └── patient_001.vcf
//   ├── reference/          # GWAS stats, ref panels, chain files
//   │   ├── gwas_cad.tsv
//   │   ├── 1000G_panel.vcf
//   │   └── hg19ToHg38.chain
//   ├── work/               # Nextflow working directory (temp files)
//   ├── results/            # final pipeline output
//   │   ├── qc/
//   │   ├── scores/
//   │   ├── database/
//   │   └── figures/
//   └── archive/            # lifecycle-managed cold storage

// ---- Lambda Trigger ----
// When a VCF lands in the input/ prefix, an S3 event notification
// triggers a Lambda function. The Lambda:
//   1. Validates the file (is it actually a VCF?)
//   2. Submits a Nextflow job to AWS Batch
//   3. Passes the S3 path as the --input_vcf parameter
//
// This means the whole pipeline is event-driven — no cron jobs,
// no manual intervention. Upload a file, get results.

// ---- CloudWatch Monitoring ----
// I set up dashboards for:
//   - CPU utilization per Batch job
//   - Memory usage (important for imputation)
//   - S3 storage usage over time
//   - Job success/failure rates
//   - Cost per pipeline run
//
// Plus CloudWatch Alarms:
//   - Alert if a job runs longer than 6 hours (something's probably wrong)
//   - Alert if memory usage exceeds 90% (need bigger instances)
//   - Alert if monthly costs exceed $100 (from AWS Budgets)

// ---- Cost Estimation ----
// For a typical run with ~1M variants and 100 samples:
//   - QC: ~5 min on c5.large ($0.01)
//   - Normalization: ~10 min on c5.large ($0.02)
//   - Imputation: ~2 hours on c5.4xlarge SPOT ($0.30 vs $1.50 on-demand)
//   - Scoring: ~15 min on c5.xlarge ($0.03)
//   - Storage: ~$0.02/month (S3 Standard)
//   - Total per run: ~$0.36 with spot vs ~$1.56 on-demand
//   - Monthly budget of $100 supports ~275 runs
